I think this can be fixed to only set event flag and start this task from `close()` method.

text:
I think this method can be simplified to look like this
```python
@asyncio.coroutine
def wait_closed(self):
    yield from self._close_state.wait()
    assert self._close_waiter is not None
    yield from asyncio.shield(self._close_waiter, loop=self._loop)
```
title: (None, '', u'aioredis/pool.py')

text:
Otherwise you should add check `if self._close_waiter is None` in `close()` method.
This also applies to sentinel pool.
title: (None, '', u'aioredis/pool.py')

text:
I don't get your point there.

If `close` is called first, it will create the `self._close_waiter` task

If `wait_closed` is called first, it will create the self._close_waiter` and then wait until `close_state` is set
title: (None, '', u'aioredis/pool.py')

text:
Yes, but it (`wait_closed`) will wait until `_close_state` is set, which is called from `close()`,
and so `_close_waiter` will be replaced with new task from `close`.
